entry.title: media/gpu/chromeos: Add storage type accessor to frame pool
entry.content:
For each frame pool this adds a method for getting the frame pool

storage type - GetFrameStorageType(). These are hard-coded to match the

storage type for frames returned by GetFrame(). Runtime checks have been

added to ensure their accuracy.



The storage type is needed for VideoDecoderPipeline to create an

ImageProcessor. Having an accessor lets us change the storage type for

any frame pool independently.



Note: for PlatformVideoFrameTool, this make the member variable |lock_|

mutable. Doing this lets a scoped lock be taken from it in const

methods. This lets GetFrameStorageType() be defined as const.

entry.title: [dPWA] Remove usage of RemoveWebAppJob in favor of removing sources.
entry.content:
Previously uninstalling a web app via user request scheduled a

RemoveWebApp job, which failed if management types were present that

should disqualify user uninstall. This is easy to hit if there was, say,

a policy install queued in the system already.



This change:

* Modifies this uninstall to instead just remove all user-

uninstallable management types.

* Fixes a bug with OS uninstall entry removal which didn't actually

add that entry when the app became user-uninstallable.

* Cleans up more of these fields to 'management' instead of 'source'.

* Makes the scheduler names more accurate.

See Patchset 1 vs 2 for what has changed from original cl. To fix

crashing checks were added to companion related code in

PinnedToolbarActionsContainer and SidePanelToolbarContainer to make sure

the companion feature is enabled before attempting to trigger the

companion migration. This was likely causing the crashing since it

appeared the majority of crash instances had side panel pinning with

responsive toolbar enabled but not companion. Also update any added

checks for the kSidePanelPinning flag to instead use

IsSidePanelPinningEnabled method which also checks the chrome refresh.



This is a reland of commit 58df1606dcc1ab89958c0d38ce7cb542aa9a4a65



Original change's description:

> [ Companion ] Migrate Companion pref into PinnedActionsToolbarModel Fix

>

> Fixes a bug where the migration of the

> `kSidePanelCompanionEntryPinnedToToolbar` profile pref only happened on

> startup / instantiation of the PinnedToolbarActionsModel even though

> the pref could be changed at any point during a browser's session.

>

> To fix this, we call the migration code any time

> CompanionUtils::UpdateCompanionDefaultPinnedToolbarState is called.

> This will attempt to migrate the pref into the

> PinnedToolbarActionsModel, if it hasn't already. All current callers

entry.title: [SAA] Implementing SharedWorker support (Part 3: Implement same-site cookie filtering)
entry.content:
TL;DR: This is a large CL, see an outline of key points under the intro.



Introduction:



The Storage Access API provides access to unpartitioned cookies in

third-party contexts. This CL is part of a series to extend that access

to SharedWorkers.



Before we actually provide access to SharedWorkers, we need a way for

the renderer to limit the scope of SameSite cookies provided to the

worker. Normally, a worker with a first-party storage key could access

all cookies, but if access is via the SAA handle we want to limit that

access to just SameSite: None cookies.



This CL is part of a series to allow that limiting ability. It

implements the filter that prevents the inclusion of SameSite=Strict/Lax

cookies in a first-party shared worker when 'sameSiteCookies': 'none' is

set.



Note: The ability to request 'all' in a third-party context is not added

here nor will it be added.



Outline:



(1) require_cross_site_request_for_cookies is calculated by checking if

the storage key is third-party or the sameSiteCookies option is none.

(2) This is calculated in three spots:

(2a) content/browser/devtools/shared_worker_devtools_agent_host.cc

(2b) content/browser/worker_host/shared_worker_host.cc

(2c) content/browser/worker_host/shared_worker_service_impl.cc

(3) Most of the CL is propagating this boolean value down to the four

key spots it's used:

(3a) services/network/cors/cors_url_loader_factory.cc verifies that if

the value is set, SiteForCookies is empty on the request.

(3b) content/browser/worker_host/shared_worker_service_impl.cc

sets the SiteForCookies used to load the script to empty.

(3c) content/renderer/worker/embedded_shared_worker_stub.cc ensures that

that on redirect we maintain the correct site for cookies.

(3d) third_party/blink/renderer/core/fetch/fetch_manager.cc

sets the SiteForCookies used to load worker fetches to empty.

(4) The WPTs verify only the proper cookies can be get/set in each

context, including worker load, worker fetch, and on redirect.



Design Doc:

https://docs.google.com/document/d/19qCGb4qwOcGiNrQM3ptWvRmB4JtpaTFgFVlWLXNOQ6c/edit



Explainer:

https://privacycg.github.io/saa-non-cookie-storage/shared-workers.html



Part 1: Expose same-site cookie IPC

Part 2: Expose same-site cookie IDL

Part 3: Implement same-site cookie filtering

Part 4: Add SharedWorker support to SAA handle

entry.title: [DIPS] Extract redirect chain detection into dedicated class.
entry.content:
This is part of the migration of DIPS from //chrome to //content.

See go/dips-move



Move all the redirect-chain-detection code out to a new

WebContentsObserver subclass, RedirectChainDetector (RCD).



Make DIPSWebContentsObserver (DipsWCO) subclass RCD::Observer.



As DipsWCO previously did a lot of processing of cookie accesses (e.g.

to ignore 3PCs, since it only deletes when 3PCs are blocked; to

attribute CHIPs to the 1P; and more) and we don't want to duplicate that

logic between RCD and DipsWCO, I moved that logic into RCD but report

the results via RCD::Observer::OnSiteStorageAccessed().



The name of RedirectChainDetector (a WebContentsObserver) is too

similar to DIPSBounceDetector (its unit-testable logic implementer),

which is no longer DIPS-specific. The latter (and other no-longer-DIPS

things) will be renamed in a future CL.



One unfortunate side-effect of the refactor is that writes to the DIPS

DB from DipsWCO are no longer unit-testable, since they are no longer

performed by DIPSBounceDetector. So the tests that writes are throttled,

for example, were rewritten as browser tests.



This refactor made it clearer that some things are written to the DIPS

DB without being considered to make bounces "stateful", namely the

events that DipsWCO observes that RCD does not (e.g. Web Workers). These

are probably oversights; if confirmed they will be moved to RCD in a

future CL.

entry.title: Migrate Suspicious Site Reporter extension users to pref
entry.content:
By default, Chrome elides certain parts of the URL from the omnibox

(www subdomain, scheme). Some users don't like this, so we built an

extension (Suspicious Site Reporter) geared at power users which

prevents URL elision and also allows them to report suspicious sites

to Safe Browsing. Later on, we built a setting directly into Chrome to

prevent URL elision.



The Suspicious Site Reporter extension is not used very much for

reporting sites and it's not longer needed for preventing URL elision since we built the setting. So the plan is to deprecate the extension. However, when we eventually get rid of it altogether, we don't want users who want URL elisions prevented to suddenly have URL elisions re-enabled. This CL migrates users who have the extension installed by setting the pref so that URL elisions won't re-appear when the extension gets killed.



The extension's behavior for URL elisions was previously implemented

by checking both for the extension installation and the pref in

ChromeLocationBarModelDelegeate. That special case is now removed, and

instead Browser checks for the extension installation upon creation

and sets the pref if the extension is installed. This code only needs

to exist for a couple milestones and then we can delete it and push an

extension update that uninstalls itself.

entry.title: Update Security FAQ about contextual menu navigations.
entry.content:
We have treated "right click > open in a new window" as similar to the

user copy-pasting the URL into a new window. As a result, many policies:

CSP / sandbox / COEP / COOP / Referrer / origin / browsing context group

/ ... are not inherited.



This is deliberate. As long as there are no strong evidences this could

harm users, we really shouldn't try doing something different. This

would:

- Add extra complexity and unresolved questions.

- Allow websites to block users from opening popups. We should consider

the intents of the users superior to the intents of the website.

- Open up the door to countess opportunities to fill up new security

bugs about: "What about inheriting xxx properties?".



There have been 20+ bug reports about this. They have all been closed as

Duplicated/WontFix. See:

- https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=1784059

- https://issues.chromium.org/issues/40060542

- https://issues.chromium.org/issues/40057000

- https://issues.chromium.org/issues/324003975

- etc...



We should clear up the ambiguity to avoid additional

security shepherd work to triage the same kind of bug over and over. We

previously agreed with Mozilla to close and make them all public

(2022-08-30).
